messages.text: How’s my baby feeling?
Still groggy?
Yeah a little.
Just stay home and rest
That’s what you need.
I’ll be home soon. I’m so sorry for leaving you home all day.
It’s fine, I’m not a baby anymore.
You’re still my baby.
If you feel queasy, take a tablespoon of the blue milk.
It’s still in that bottle above the bathroom sink.
Okay, will do.
You should take it now.
I feel fine, I just want to try to get some homework done.
Homework on your day off?
Wow, you really are the little workhorse.
I’m falling behind.
Because I’ve been out sick so much.
Your teachers will understand.
Do you want me to call?
No.
I just need to make sure I have an A in chemistry.
Before I start sending out college apps.
Well, I don’t want you overdoing it.
If you feel faint, just lie down.
I’ll be home soon.
the next day
Mom, my stomach hurts.
Aww, poor baby.
I can come pick you up.
I knew sending you to school today was a bad idea.
But I had an entire cup of the blue milk — Milk of Magnesia or whatever.
I thought it would make me feel better.
You know that resting is the only real cure.
I’m on my way.
a few hours later
I’ll be home in an hour. Don’t get up from your bed, please.
You know that makes it worse.
What if I start feeling better?
I have this group project with Alan. I need to work on it later.
I’m calling your teacher, then.
You shouldn’t be working when you feel like this.
Take another glass of Milk of Magnesia.
A whole glass?
I have cramps, Mom. I’m not DYING.
That’s what you think.
But you need to trust my judgment.
Please do as I say, and I will call your chem teacher.
Fine.
Jen sees a new text from her friend Alan.
They’ve been friends since kindergarten…
And she’s always hoped there would be something more between them.
Hey Jen, are you coming over to work on the project?
My mom won’t let me out.
Can we come to your house?
We really need your smarty-pants expertise.
My mom wouldn’t like it.
No offense, but I feel like your mom doesn’t like it when you do anything.
She’s an RN.
So she gets overprotective when I’m sick.
Seems like you’re sick an awful lot.
I have weird stomach issues.
The doctors haven’t been able to figure it out.
The only thing that seems to help is Milk of Magnesia.
What is this, the 1950s?
Who takes that stuff anymore?
It’s what my mom gives me.
I’m coming over.
Without the group.
I just want to see you.
Text me when you’re here.
Already am.
I parked down the street and let myself in the front door.
I can’t believe you still keep a key under the mat.
Intruder alert!
Lol, you know you can trust me.
I’ll be up to your bedroom in one minute.
Just want to see something.
Creeper…
Umm, Jen, can you come to your mother’s bathroom?
WTF, Alan? Why are you in there?
I need to show you something.
Is your mom by any chance into repairing cars?
No??
Because she has like a gallon of antifreeze under her sink.
Hold on, I’m coming.
Crap, I hear her car pulling up. You need to leave.
Go through the side door.
She’ll kill me if she knows I have friends over.
the next morning
You coming to school today?
No. Mom says I’m not well enough to go.
Jen, whatever you do, do not drink that Milk of Magnesia.
Why?
I think you know why.
There’s a good chance it’s toxic.
What the hell, Alan?
Is this your way of flirting?
Sneaking into my house and then telling me what to do?
Jen, you know I care about you.
I have for over ten years.
Which is why I’m warning you: do not drink that milk!
Fine.
Jen gets a text from her mother.
I’ll be home much later tonight. Drink your Milk and get some rest.
Sure thing, Mom.
Jen switches over to her thread with Alan.
I just lied to my mom. I hope you’re happy.
Have you ever heard of Munchausen’s by Proxy?
We learned about it last week in Psych.
Isn’t that when people fake being sick for attention?
Wow, you really don’t get it, do you?
No! That’s Munchausen’s Syndrome.
Munchausen’s by Proxy is different. It means your mom is trying to hurt you.
All she does is help me.
Really? How do you feel today?
Better than yesterday, I guess.
And what’s changed?
I didn’t drink the milk.
Exactly. Your mom is putting antifreeze in your Milk of Magnesia.
That’s crazy! Why would she TRY to get me sick?
When you told her you wanted to go to UCLA, how did she respond?
She said there was no way I was moving that far.
When I asked you to homecoming, how did she respond?
She said I shouldn’t be dating at my age.
When you want to work on a group project FOR SCHOOL, how does she respond?
She says no.
Do the math, smarty-pants.
She’s trying to imprison you so you’ll never leave her.
Oh my god.
Even if you’re right, what can I do?
My mom is my whole life. It’s just the two of us.
It’s going to be just one of you pretty soon.
What does that mean?
Think about it. Either she poisons you to death, or…
No! That’s impossible!
I’m cutting class and coming to your house.
Hold on…
Jen texts her mother.
Mom, I feel much better. I should go to school.
Impossible. Did you take your milk?
Yeah, and it gave me strength.
Let me go.
You need rest. I’m coming home right now.
Jen switches back to her thread with Alan.
Quick, my mom is on her way home.
Use the front door, the key’s still under the mat.
I’m already on your block.
She’s here. Forget it.
Jen hears her mother running up the stairs and then a knock on her door.
Jennifer, let me in your room.
Why is the door locked?
I’m scared.
Of what? Let me in to help you.
No. You’re only trying to hurt me.
How? That’s such nonsense. Let me in.
Jen’s mother bangs on the bedroom door…
Just as Alan sneaks into the house through the front door.
Did you invite friends over? Are you in there with someone?
Jennifer, you are in huge trouble.
Come on. Let Mommy in. We used to be best friends.
I promise we can do whatever you want this weekend.
We can go get pedicures and see that new movie.
Jen gets a text from Alan.
I’m in.
Come on sweetie. I promise, everything’s gonna be okay.
Jen opens the door and as her mother enters—
Alan sneaks in behind her.
Jen’s mother whirls around to see Alan standing in the doorway defiantly.
She grabs Jen’s arm and thrusts her behind her own back.
What are you doing in my house?!
Let her go! The cops are on the way!
The cops? For what? For treating my sick daughter?
You’re poisoning her! That milk is full of toxic chemicals!
Don’t listen to him, honey. Drink your milk.
Mommy knows best. Drink up!
No! I don’t want to!
Just do it! I’m a nurse, I know better than some teenager!
Jen’s mother takes the glass of the milk she brought and forces it to Jen’s lips.
Alan throws himself between them and knocks Jen’s mother to the side.
Two officers enter through the front door, which Alan left unlocked.
Hello? This is the police.
Help! I’ve been attacked!
An Officer walks into Jen’s bedroom and surveys the scene.
What’s going on here? Who called us?
Officer, thank god! This man is trying to attack me!
He’s been stalking my sick daughter. He broke in and tackled me!
No! I’m the one who called 911.
This woman is poisoning her daughter!
Here.
Alan grabs the cup from Jen’s mother and hands it to the officer.
She’s been giving her daughter antifreeze. Test this, you’ll see.
The officer skeptically takes the cup from Alan, glancing between all three of them.
All three of you need to come down to the station with us and file a report.
Separate Reports.
The officer puts his hand on Alan’s shoulder, guiding him out of the room.
He looks back at Jen and her mother.
He sees the shock on Jen’s face as she stares after Alan.
I think it’s best if you ride with me, ma’am.
My partner can take your daughter and her friend.
Her mother turns to her and looks into her eyes.
Everything’s going to be okay sweetie, you’ll see.
Mommy knows best.
She turns and leaves the room.
You coming over to study today?
Yeah. My foster mom said I can borrow the car.
Maybe we can do more than just study…😉
You’re insatiable!
What can I say, we’ve got some time to make up for 🙂
I’ll see you soon.
As Jen goes to grab the car keys off the kitchen counter…
She sees her foster brother left out a glass of a milk on the table.
She grabs it and dumps it down the sink.
And walks out of the house into the sunshine.
